q {
Q:"If \\(\\sin^{-1}x + \\sin^{-1}y + \\sin^{-1}z = \\frac{3\\pi}{2}\\) then the value of \\(x^9 + y^9 + z^9 - \\frac{1}{x^9 y^9 z^9}\\) is equal to:"
A:"c"
O:a) "0", b) "1", c) "2", d) "3"
R:"The maximum value of \\(\\sin^{-1}\\theta\\) is \\(\\pi/2\\). For the sum to be \\(3\\pi/2\\), each term must be \\(\\pi/2\\), so \\(x=y=z=1\\). Substituting gives \\(1+1+1 - 1 = 2\\)."
}

q {
Q:"Let \\(p, q, r\\) be sides opposite to angles \\(P, Q, R\\) in \\(\\Delta PQR\\). If \\(r^2 \\sin P \\sin Q = pq\\), then the triangle is:"
A:"d"
O:a) "Equilateral", b) "Acute angled but not equilateral", c) "Obtuse angled", d) "Right angled"
R:"Using sine rule \\(p=k\\sin P, q=k\\sin Q, r=k\\sin R\\). Substitution yields \\(\\sin^2 R = 1 \\Rightarrow R = 90^\\circ\\). Hence, right angled."
}

q {
Q:"In \\(\\Delta PQR\\), \\(2pr \\sin\\left(\\frac{P-Q+R}{2}\\right)\\) equals:"
A:"b"
O:a) "\\(p^2+q^2+r^2\\)", b) "\\(p^2+r^2-q^2\\)", c) "\\(q^2+r^2-p^2\\)", d) "\\(p^2+q^2-r^2\\)"
R:"Since \\(P+R = \\pi - Q\\), the angle becomes \\(\\frac{\\pi}{2} - Q\\). Thus, \\(\\sin(\\dots) = \\cos Q\\). By cosine rule, \\(2pr \\cos Q = p^2+r^2-q^2\\)."
}

q {
Q:"Let \\(P(2,-3)\\), \\(Q(-2,1)\\) be vertices of \\(\\Delta PQR\\). If centroid lies on \\(2x+3y=1\\), locus of \\(R\\) is:"
A:"a"
O:a) "\\(2x+3y=9\\)", b) "\\(2x-3y=9\\)", c) "\\(3x+2y=5\\)", d) "\\(3x-2y=5\\)"
R:"Centroid \\(G = (h/3, (k-2)/3)\\). Substituting into line eq: \\(2(h/3) + 3((k-2)/3) = 1 \\Rightarrow 2h+3k=9\\). Locus: \\(2x+3y=9\\)."
}

